Polymorphism is an OOP concept that allows an object to take multiple forms. It means that a single action, method, or interface can represent different behaviors depending on the context.

In simple terms:
Polymorphism allows you to write code that works with general types while letting specific objects decide how they behave.
Why do we need polymorphism?

Without polymorphism, you might write separate code for every object type.

Example
1)without polymorphism

Dog dog = new Dog();
dog.bark();
Cat cat = new Cat();
cat.meow();

This works, but imagine having 100 different animals. You would need to check every type and call the correct method manually.

2)With polymorphism:

Animal animal;
animal = new Dog();
animal.makeSound();

animal = new Cat();
animal.makeSound();

The program automatically knows which version of makeSound() to execute.

The two main types of polymorphism

1. Compile-time Polymorphism (Static Polymorphism)
This happens when the compiler decides which method to call.
It is achieved through method overloading.

2. Runtime Polymorphism (Dynamic Polymorphism)
This happens when the decision is made while the program is running.
It is achieved through method overriding.